\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Approach}
Forget about historic information temporarily and use linear programming,
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ll}
\max\limits_{\mathbf{\mathcal{X}_t}} &\mathbb{E}_{\xi}\left(\sum\limits^T_{t=1} \sum\limits^J_{j=1} v_j X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j})\right)\\
s.t. & 0\leq X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j}) \leq \xi_{t,j}\\
& \sum\limits_{t=1}^T\sum\limits^J_{j=1} A X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j}) \leq 2\mathbf{c} - \mathbb{E}(\sum\limits_{t=1}^T \sum\limits^J_{j=1} A X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j}))\\
&\forall \xi \in \Xi,t=1,\ldots,T
\end{array}
\label{originthird}
\end{equation}
where $L(\xi_{t,j})$ lift $\xi_{t,j}$ to values of basis functions,and $X_{t,j}$ is actually coefficient matrixes.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Details in above equation}
\begin{itemize}
\item It's not hard to prove that shapes of $X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j})$ will be something like we required. So we can get booking limits from maximum of $X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j})$ and then implement polices.
\item $\mathbf{c} - \mathbb{E}(\sum\limits_{t=1}^T \sum\limits^J_{j=1} A X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j}))$ is added to ensure that we can make use of resources as much as possible. In fact, $\sum\limits_{t=1}^T\sum\limits^J_{j=1} A X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j}) \approx 2\mathbf{c} - \mathbb{E}(\sum\limits_{t=1}^T \sum\limits^J_{j=1} A X_{t,j} L(\xi_{t,j}))$.So expectations of used resources will be $c$.
\end{itemize}
Now we turn to problems of making use of historic information.
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Historic information}
Remember that we didn't give $L(\xi_t)$ a specific form.

Doing triangulations in 2-dimension, we can approximate original problems with $X(\sum\limits_{\tau=1}^{t-1} \xi_{\tau},\xi_t)$ now.
